ninkrijk","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"about 1135–1205":"about 1135–1205","1135–1205":"1135–1205","1150–Female":"1150–Deceased","1170–1252":"1170–1252","1180–1232":"1180–1232","1186–Male":"1186–Deceased","1120–1174":"1120–1174","about 1170":"about 1170","1120":"1120","1186":"1186","1252":"1252","1174":"1174","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","abt. 1186":"about 1186","1205":"1205","1135":"1135","1232":"1232","about 1135":"about 1135","about 1174":"about 1174","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Skipwith, Yorkshire, England":"Skipwith, Yorkshire, England","Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Skipwith","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Surrey): variant of   Skipworth  .","History: The main Skipwith family held the manor of Skipwith in England in the early Middle Ages, and direct descendants can be traced to the present day. In the 13th century they moved from Yorkshire to Lincolnshire, where their principal seat was at southern Ormsby. In the early 17th century there was further migration, to Leicestershire, Warwickshire, and across the Atlantic to VA. Other bearers of the name seem to have been tenants of Lincolnshire manors held by the Skipworth family, and to have taken the surname of their overlords."],"variants":[{"name":"Skipworth","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): habitational name from Skipwith (East Yorkshire), from Old Northumbrian <i>scīp</i> (Old English <i>scēap</i> ‘sheep’), + Old English <i>wīc</i> ‘dwelling, specialized farm’, later replaced by Old Norse <i>vithr</i> ‘wood’; initial <i>Sk-</i>, instead of <i>Sh-</i>, is also due to Scandinavian influence."]}]},{"name":"Jeffrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Geoffrey  , common in the Middle Ages (as reflected in surnames such as <i>Jefferson</i>). This is now the usual spelling of the name both in North America and Britain. Well-known bearers include the novelist and former British politician  Jeffrey Archer  (  b. 1940 ), the British conductor  Jeffrey Tate  (  b. 1943 ), and the American soul singer  Jeffrey Osborne  (  b. 1951 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeffery","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Geoffrey  , common in the Middle Ages (as reflected in surnames such as <i>Jefferson</i>). This is now the usual spelling of the name both in North America and Britain. Well-known bearers include the novelist and former British politician  Jeffrey Archer  (  b. 1940 ), the British conductor  Jeffrey Tate  (  b. 1943 ), and the American soul singer  Jeffrey Osborne  (  b. 1951 )."]},{"name":"Jeffry","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Geoffrey  , common in the Middle Ages (as reflected in surnames such as <i>Jefferson</i>). This is now the usual spelling of the name both in North America and Britain. Well-known bearers include the novelist and former British politician  Jeffrey Archer  (  b. 1940 ), the British conductor  Jeffrey Tate  (  b. 1943 ), and the American soul singer  Jeffrey Osborne  (  b. 1951 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Je